English Summary

Under the Loan. Lending trends by industry

This newsletter outlines a concerning trend in the decline of foreign currency loans to the industrial sector, indicating a contraction in real industry. Economic growth, however, has been primarily boosted by the re-export of precious metals, notably gold, highlighting a dependency on external factors. Despite a decrease in foreign currency loans to the trade sector, theres a positive offset with an increase in Armenian dram loans, particularly noticeable in agriculture and construction sectors.

On the other hand, theres a worrying increase in mortgage and consumer loans, with mortgage loans surpassing 10 percent of GDP by April 2024, compared to just 2.5 percent in 2018. This shift in lending patterns is reflected in a decrease in the share of industry and trade loans, while consumer and mortgage loans now dominate over half of all loans. These trends raise concerns regarding economic stability, especially considering the downward trend in overall lending and economic contraction indicators, suggesting a potential overreliance on unsustainable factors like gold re-exports for economic growth.
